1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,000
But when you mistake a map for the world, you've made a huge error, and I believe that's where we now are.

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:14,000
These seem to be the primary paths to reality. One is science, another is reason.

3
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:23,000
A third is imagination, and a force is intuition. And we live in an era in which imagination and intuition have been sort of tarnished as false.

4
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:27,000
Hello and welcome to the Science Fiction podcast with Daniel Walter.

5
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:36,000
Long-term listeners to the podcast will have followed our evolving journey in what we're talking about when we talk about science fiction.

6
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:45,000
So sometimes the Science Fiction podcast is a fancast for Denis Villeneuve and his upcoming June 2 movie.

7
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:54,000
But we're also trying to discuss the what happens when science and fiction meet.

8
00:00:54,000 --> 00:01:03,000
These apparently very two opposite things, science, which is all about the facts and realities of our world and fiction, which is all about the stories.

9
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:10,000
And we've encapsulated this in our logo with a series of words that represent something of a duality.

10
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:20,000
So science and fiction, reality and fantasy, reason and emotion and mythos and logos.

11
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:32,000
And I'm incredibly honored today to be joined by, I think, the leading thinker in the world about this apparent division that runs through our culture

12
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:43,000
and seems to run through humanity. And it seems to run really down the center of our brain and the two hemispheres of our brain.

13
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:48,000
So I'm really happy to welcome Ian McGillchrist. Hello and welcome, Ian.

14
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:50,000
Oh, thank you, Damon. I'm delighted to be here.

15
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:53,000
Well, thank you for joining me. It is literally a tremendous honor.

16
00:01:53,000 --> 00:02:04,000
I've spent dozens and dozens of hours listening to you on other people's podcasts and to your audio explorations of your most recent book as well.

17
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:12,000
I wonder if I can ask you, I hope this isn't a left field question for you, and it would be totally okay to say no.

18
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:19,000
But do you have any relationship to science fiction? Would you say you're a science fiction fan?

19
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:26,000
Some people really dislike science fiction, and if that was you, that would be fine as well. That would be an interesting direction.

20
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:31,000
No, I mean, I certainly don't dislike science fiction. I don't know a lot of science fiction.

21
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:47,000
And one of the sad things about the last 30 years is that I've had to keep up with so many science and philosophy books that I haven't really had much time for reading things that are sort of perhaps more tangential,

22
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:58,000
but nonetheless important. There are some works of science fiction that I consider of colossal status, and one is Stanislas Lem's Solaris.

23
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:07,000
And I think that Tarkovsky's exploration of it is extraordinarily inexhaustibly deep. I've seen it many, many times.

24
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:14,000
I've also seen the other film called Solaris Made in America, but it was so disappointing that I don't refer to it anymore.

25
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:29,000
But there's that. And I've also been reading something that probably isn't science fiction exactly, which is C.S. Lewis's, he did three, a three-part trilogy.

26
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:42,000
And I've only read the third part, which is called that hideous strength. And it is a kind of science fiction, but it's also very much a sort of mythology, and it's very powerful.

27
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:50,000
And very prescient, by the way. I mean, in 1945 or whenever he was writing it, he was foreseeing things that have happened recently.

28
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:59,000
Fantastic. That was one of my introductions to science fiction. And yes, I would definitely say that Lewis's space trilogy is science fiction.

29
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Yes.

30
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:15,000
And also, of course, theological as well. And as always, definitely creating a myth for the future, which is one of the ways that I discuss science fiction.

31
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:18,000
I talk about science fiction as modern mythmaking.

32
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:19,000
Yes.

33
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:32,000
So Tolkien is, I mean, generally considered a fantasy writer, but fantasy and science fiction are very related. And he had his ideas of myth appear, the creation of myths for the world.

34
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:41,000
No, I was hoping that we would explore some of this overlap with myth and science fiction between us today.

35
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:59,000
Absolutely. Yes. Yes. Well, as you know, because you've read my work, mythos in the ancient Greek was prior to and more important than logos from which we derive the word logic.

36
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:09,000
I mean, logos didn't mean logic in those days. It meant things that were more explicit. It meant things that you could argue for in a court of law or, you know, in a debate.

37
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:27,000
But mythos was the only way of capturing the really serious, important, emotional, philosophical thoughts about the world that are hard to put into everyday language, but are nonetheless important for that.

38
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:42,000
And we seem to live in a time where for a long time, especially in Western culture, we seem to maybe deny mythos to say it wasn't significant to us anymore.

39
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:48,000
We could be a culture purely of logos. And I know we're going to get more into this with your ideas.

40
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:59,000
But then I see the way that our attempt to do that was completely futile because the mythos is really more powerful than we are.

41
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:09,000
And it just exploded up again. And one major way of that happening was science fiction and the huge popularity of, of course, things like Star Wars and Star Trek.

42
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:19,000
But movies like 2001, and of course the popularity of writers like, like Lewis, who make this explicitly theological as well.

43
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:28,000
Yes, yes. Your expression, it's bigger than we are, is rather important, I think.

44
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:36,000
There's a sense in which these things are not made up, but are permitted by us to come to expression.

45
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:47,000
And when one is writing the most difficult to express things, and then suddenly poetry, of which I have a little experienced,

46
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:58,000
one feels that something is writing through you. It's not that it doesn't use you and take part of you into it, but it's not just coming out of view.

47
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:06,000
That's the very strong feeling one has. And so many artists and writers have reported very much the same phenomenon.

48
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:14,000
Yeah, absolutely. That was, I think we'll get to that in one of my questions. I don't want to pre-empt too much here.

49
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:25,000
What I'd like to do for my listeners is discuss your work for which you're best known, which is articulated in two books.

50
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:35,000
The Master and His Emissary in 2009, and The Matter with Things in 2021. Both very significant books.

51
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:48,000
I think I cropped up a couple of times in your live events as the person who said that The Matter with Things is a three and a half pencil book to get through it

52
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:58,000
and deal with all of the questions that come up. And the complete works of Shakespeare is only two and a half pencils.

53
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:14,000
But would it be fair to say that The Master and His Emissary is your thesis of the dual hemispheric model, and then The Matter with Things is the extended philosophy?

54
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:28,000
I think that's a good way of putting it. The only thing I would add to that is that I explored literature that wasn't available when I first was writing The Master and His Emissary.

55
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:42,000
And so in The Matter with Things, I include a great deal more neuro-psychological evidence. I think it's about 6,000 papers and sources that are referred to there.

56
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:48,000
So nobody can say there's no evidence. That doesn't stop some people saying that without having looked at my books.

57
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:58,000
I'm trying to get beyond that. So yes, it is. And it's saying what the philosophical encourt of all this is.

58
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:08,000
In a second, I'm going to ask you to give your summary, I guess, which you must be very used to doing by now.

59
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:21,000
I think one of the important points is that this does have these very deep roots in scientific research in various areas that you have crossed into.

60
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:34,000
So that separates it from the pop culture idea of hemispheres, which people are quite familiar with, and then have also heard it is no longer valid.

61
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:52,000
So that's something to say that this goes significantly beyond that idea. And also it has a lot of similarities to a long history of thinking about the world that we might think of through the mythos or even through religions.

62
00:09:53,000 --> 00:10:09,000
And perhaps even ideas today, like you've talked to people about John the Vakie, about meaning and so on. It crosses into all of these areas, but yours seems to be the most scientifically rigorous of them.

63
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:11,000
Is that fair, do you think?

64
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:27,000
I think so, yes. And it's not only that I take up this unpopular issue of hemisphere difference, but I come to quite different conclusions from the ones that made their way into popular culture.

65
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:35,000
So the first hurdle I always have to get over is, oh, all that stuff about hemispheres was exploded long ago. It's pop science and it's nonsense.

66
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:48,000
Well, it's true that most of, not all, but most of what was said about hemisphere differences was wrong. But perhaps I could explain what I think is important about the difference.

67
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:50,000
Please do.

68
00:10:50,000 --> 00:11:00,000
First of all, it's a very evolutionarily verifiable hypothesis, if you like.

69
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:16,000
The idea is that the two hemispheres of the brain evolved differently, not just in human beings, but in pretty much all creatures we've looked at, to solve a particular problem, which is how to pay two kinds of attention to the world at the same time.

70
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:26,000
One kind of attention is required for survival in the simplest sense, that we need to get stuff, we need to grab food, we need to catch a rabbit, we need to pick up a seed, whatever it is.

71
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:34,000
And we need also to be able to manipulate our environment to pick things up and build things and use tools and so on in the case of human beings.

72
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:49,000
So, in fact, as far back as we can go in history, 700 million years, we know that the neural networks that formed the ancestors of the human brain were asymmetrical, which is interesting in itself.

73
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:51,000
Why were they asymmetrical?

74
00:11:52,000 --> 00:12:05,000
And I think the reason for this was that, as I say, two kinds of attention need to be paid. One is the one with which we grab things, and so this is the one subtended by us, in us, by the left hemisphere.

75
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:20,000
And it therefore pays attention to something that we already know what it is, we know we want it, and we need to get it, and so it focuses in a targeted way, a very narrow beam of attention that brings clarity.

76
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:26,000
But the difficulty with this is that it is not seeing everything else that's going on at the same time.

77
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:38,000
And so in order to survive, you also need to be looking out for predators, not just predators, but also for your kin, for your offspring, for your mate, for your kind.

78
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:58,000
And to do this, you need precisely the opposite kind of attention, maximally open, undedicated yet as to what it may find, and broad, sustained, and on the lookout vigilant.

79
00:12:58,000 --> 00:13:06,000
So, very different from this, I know what it is, I want to get it, it's a detail. The right hemisphere is looking out for the whole of the rest of it.

80
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:21,000
So, the one thing that was probably true about what people used to say was that the left hemisphere had a narrow attention and the right hemisphere broad attention, and that's not disputed by anyone in the world, and it's a very well-attested fact.

81
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:34,000
But what people were not aware of so much was that attention creates the experiential world. What we find to be there depends on the kind of attention we pay.

82
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:43,000
And there are many amusing experiments that have been done in recent years showing that we're completely blind to something we don't expect to see.

83
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:54,000
And so, what follows for me is that these kinds of attention give rise to two different kinds of phenomenological worlds. What are they like?

84
00:13:54,000 --> 00:14:06,000
In a nutshell, the left hemisphere sees things that are already known, familiar, fixed, isolated, fragmentary, decontextualized, and examples of a kind, a category.

85
00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:17,000
Not unique, but oh, it's one of those. And this kind of abstracted thinking is a useful tool, but it's not very good for constructing reality.

86
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:33,000
The right hemisphere sees something much more complex. It sees a world in which nothing is completely, fully known, is never completely fixed, is never completely isolated, but is ultimately in connection with everything else.

87
00:14:33,000 --> 00:14:52,000
It's flowing, it's changing, it's often implicit. The right hemisphere is much better, sorry, this is my right hemisphere, at picking up the stuff that is hard to detect with the kind of conscious mind.

88
00:14:53,000 --> 00:15:11,000
So, small changes in expression in the face, aspects of tone of voice, irony, metaphor, the language of poetry, the language of myths, it's much better at understanding the meaning of a story, whereas the left hemisphere sees it as simply a sequence of vignettes.

89
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:14,000
It doesn't understand the overall import of what's going on.

90
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:30,000
So, those are really quite different worlds. And my thesis is that the world that we're in now has come to depend very heavily on this very simple, mechanistic, theoretical vision of the world.

91
00:15:30,000 --> 00:15:41,000
A distinction I like to make is between presence and a representation. And a representation means literally present again after the fact, when it's actually no longer present.

92
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:51,000
So, the world is present in all its richness and complexity and intuitive meaning that can never be fully grasped to the right hemisphere, which is an expert at decoding it.

93
00:15:51,000 --> 00:16:08,000
And the left hemisphere instead replaces reality with its own simple map of reality. Now, a map is not to be despised, a map is very useful, but when you mistake a map for the world, you've made a huge error, and I believe that's where we now are.

94
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:22,000
I'd just like to add that in the ways in which we can come to a sense of what we can rely on, we need to be using, I would say, at least four things. These seem to be the primary paths to reality.

95
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:34,000
One is science. Another is reason. A third is imagination and a force is intuition. And we live in an era in which imagination and intuition have been sort of tarnished as false.

96
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:43,000
But actually science and reason can lead you to false conclusions unless they are sophisticated by imagination and intuition.

97
00:16:43,000 --> 00:16:54,000
And indeed, when you come to look at, as I have done, the stories of many great findings by mathematicians and scientists, they made these discoveries not by pursuing the scientific method as such,

98
00:16:54,000 --> 00:17:05,000
but by having a broad attention which saw new shapes, new forms, new, as the Germans say, gestalten, which are holes that cannot be decomposed into their parts without loss.

99
00:17:05,000 --> 00:17:14,000
And in each of these paths, science, reason, intuition and imagination, the right hemisphere pays the bigger part. It is actually more intelligent.

100
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:21,000
It sees more. It's emotional and social intelligence. You will not be surprised to learn as greater, but it's cognitive intelligence.

101
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:34,000
Its IQ is higher than that of the left, which is contrary to what a lot of people think. And it's much more able to feel its way into an understanding of what it is seeing in the world around it.

102
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:59,000
But these values of imagination and intuition, I guess one way I think about it is that they give us like broad long-term outcomes and the less left hemispheric values, reason and logic seem to give us like immediate and very measurable outcomes.

103
00:17:59,000 --> 00:18:20,000
And they seem, I think, the reason, for instance, among the listeners of my podcast who are often very scientifically minded, there's quite a major divide, they would say, well, we get the machines and the technology from this, what they might consider the whole process of consciousness,

104
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:35,000
but what you would call the left hemispheric. So is that why we currently value the left hemisphere more? Because it gives us the machines, it gives us the technology and those seem to represent all of our progress at the moment.

105
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:52,000
Yes, I mean it takes us a little way and I don't know how much to go into, but to concentrate on something very clear, the left hemisphere's aim is control and power.

106
00:18:53,000 --> 00:19:03,000
That's why it's in service of manipulating the world and getting stuff, grabbing stuff, it controls the right hand with which for most of us we do the manipulation.

107
00:19:04,000 --> 00:19:24,000
And so its resultant is to increase power and machines and technology are ways of externalizing this kind of thinking, but what I want to impress on any listener is that, and the full argument is in my books,

108
00:19:25,000 --> 00:19:42,000
but the vision that the left hemisphere brings is woefully deficient, it's extraordinarily lacking in an understanding of context, which changes everything, of implicit meaning, of holes that can't be degraded into parts.

109
00:19:42,000 --> 00:19:54,000
It focuses on things that are supposedly precise and builds from there as we make a machine, but actually nothing in the world except the machines we have made has this structure, nothing.

110
00:19:54,000 --> 00:20:03,000
Living things certainly don't and the inanimate world also does not. It is not mechanical, it is not made in a machine-like way.

111
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:11,000
So in order to understand we need to greatly sophisticate our intelligence and our insight, and this comes from espousing both hemispheres.

112
00:20:11,000 --> 00:20:23,000
And I'd just like to comment on the word reason. I make a distinction which is hard to make in English between what I call reason and what I call rationalization or rationalizing.

113
00:20:23,000 --> 00:20:33,000
And in other languages, there are two different words for this, for example, in German, what I call reason is called vernonz, and what I'm calling rationalizing is called verstand.

114
00:20:33,000 --> 00:20:42,000
So verstand or rationalizing is a procedural thing which you do explicitly on a paper, if this, then that, and so on and so forth. Nothing wrong with it.

115
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:49,000
But there is something that's much greater than that, which is the ability to set all this into an overall context.

116
00:20:49,000 --> 00:21:00,000
And that's something that comes with leading a wise life, and it's the sort of thing that you would expect from a good judge that at the end of his or her career,

117
00:21:00,000 --> 00:21:10,000
he was able to see the whole picture and understand in the round to take into account many, many factors in reaching a conclusion.

118
00:21:10,000 --> 00:21:19,000
And if you do that, you are less often caught out by reality. If you purely rationalize, you make some very strange steps.

119
00:21:19,000 --> 00:21:29,000
An amusing thing for me is that, I mean, a lot of time in my career, I've spent with patients with schizophrenia, of course.

120
00:21:29,000 --> 00:21:34,000
And in schizophrenia, people talk about madness and they say it's the loss of reason.

121
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:47,000
But as has been pointed out by various people, including Minkowski, a very fine Polish-French philosopher and psychiatrist in the first part of the 20th century,

122
00:21:47,000 --> 00:22:00,000
but also by others like G.K. Chesterton, the madman is someone who has lost everything but reason, can only rely on reason, and it leads to mad conclusions.

123
00:22:00,000 --> 00:22:09,000
So the person who hears a voice and there's nobody in the room thinks, well, that's strange, it's not coming from me, so what is there in this room?

124
00:22:09,000 --> 00:22:19,000
There's a socket over there in the wall. Somebody has wired into that, is beaming voices into my head. It's kind of logical, but of course it's utterly bonkers.

125
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:32,000
So we need to be careful. Intuition can, if unguided by reason, lead to falsity, but reason unguided by intuition can surely lead to falsity.

126
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:46,000
Can I lay something out for you and potentially as a mirror of this divide? Do you know Stanley Kubrick's 2001?

127
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:51,000
Yes, I do. I saw it a very long time ago and I can't remember it very well.

128
00:22:51,000 --> 00:23:06,000
Of course. Well, it seems that we've been trying to find kind of a story for how to visualize our reality.

129
00:23:06,000 --> 00:23:22,000
We had a great mythos, like the Christian mythos in the Western world, and then we came more and more to science and to reason maybe these lefts hemispheric values by going too far in that direction.

130
00:23:23,000 --> 00:23:39,000
And then we've been trying to find like a new story to put in its place, and I think science fiction represents an attempt at that story in some ways, that we're going to build space rockets and teleporters and starships.

131
00:23:39,000 --> 00:23:55,000
And this will take us off into the galaxy, into the universe, but which is this completely unconscious place, just full of dead matter and maybe some alien civilizations as well.

132
00:23:55,000 --> 00:24:06,000
But then in a movie like 2001, Stanley Kubrick, if you remember, he shows you all of the spaceships and the satellites around Earth.

133
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:12,000
But then it's not via those that we actually go out into space.

134
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:27,000
He actually has the astronaut climb inside the mind of how the artificial intelligence and switch it off, and then we go on this kind of psychedelic journey into outer space.

135
00:24:27,000 --> 00:24:42,000
So I'm sorry to test you with a film you only vaguely remember, but does that seem to express some of this divide between the hemispheres as an idea, just in the way that I've laid it out for you?

136
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:58,000
I think it does, but I caution about the divide because I make a distinction between division in the sense of complete separation and division in the sense of making a distinction.

137
00:24:58,000 --> 00:25:01,000
And there is a distinction between these hemispheres.

138
00:25:01,000 --> 00:25:11,000
One of the myths that I need to stamp on is that the left hemisphere is the hemisphere of science, and the right hemisphere is the hemisphere of sort of fantasy.

139
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:21,000
It certainly not. It is the hemisphere that's much better at imagination. But to go off on a hair, which I won't pursue unless you want me to, imagination is almost the opposite of fantasy.

140
00:25:21,000 --> 00:25:28,000
Fantasy takes us away from reality. Imagination enables us to enter into reality.

141
00:25:28,000 --> 00:25:37,000
But yes, I think you're right. I mean, one thing to say right away is that there is no conflict between Christianity and science.

142
00:25:37,000 --> 00:25:53,000
This is something that has been drummed up only since the middle of the 19th century by people who, I suppose, looking at it most charitably, they wanted to make sure that there weren't religious constraints on what could be claimed.

143
00:25:53,000 --> 00:26:16,000
And that, of course, I would back. But religion and the myth of Christianity, which is probably the most rich myth that we've ever created, if we created, is something that speaks of exactly what the best of the left and right hemisphere can bring about.

144
00:26:16,000 --> 00:26:32,000
But what happens whenever you have a myth, and if you have a religious myth, is that the left hemisphere wants to codify it. It wants to create a lot of rather odd propositions that you must sign up to, and it wants to structure it in a logical way.

145
00:26:32,000 --> 00:26:41,000
And so whole bodies of dogma are created by the left hemisphere, imposing this on religion, which is not the wellspring of religion.

146
00:26:41,000 --> 00:26:55,000
The wellspring of religion is something that is carefully responded to by patient attention, by listening to things that you don't expect to hear, understanding the speaking to you of everything around you.

147
00:26:55,000 --> 00:27:16,000
And so when, again, you talk about dead matter, and again, how long have you got? But I mean, you know, I argue in the matter with things that, in fact, consciousness is not something that sort of emerged late in the day out of a brain, but it is, in fact, a primary element, what's called an ontological primitive in the universe.

148
00:27:16,000 --> 00:27:42,000
There's so much rich stuff in there in relation to this topic. There's something that I've observed, and it's quite widely observed, often among writers of science fiction, which is that the kind of the collective imagination is more and more literal in its interpretation of any story that's given to it.

149
00:27:42,000 --> 00:27:43,000
Absolutely.

150
00:27:43,000 --> 00:28:03,000
So for any half decent writer, if you're writing about space rockets and planets and alien civilizations, there's some level in which you're exploring kind of scientific ideas, but there's also the symbolic and the metaphoric and the mythic in there as well.

151
00:28:03,000 --> 00:28:09,000
But it's harder and harder for people to think in that way at the moment.

152
00:28:09,000 --> 00:28:24,000
Absolutely. And one of the most striking things for me is that the left hemisphere doesn't understand anything that is not literal. So it really doesn't understand the point of poetry. Why lie when you could say it clearly?

153
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:40,000
It doesn't understand music. It doesn't understand irony. It doesn't understand sarcasm. It doesn't understand wit or humor. And so what you find is that people take everything incredibly literally and miss the point.

154
00:28:40,000 --> 00:28:57,000
So the vanishment of humor from public discourse in the recent years has been one of the most grievous losses to humanity that I can imagine, because in humor, although we think of it as just an entertaining element, it's actually a very profound element.

155
00:28:57,000 --> 00:29:18,000
And it's also got its place in spiritual traditions, above all in Zen, which uses tumor to help us see things that are not logically, reductively explicit. So, yeah, I mean, this is happening everywhere.

156
00:29:18,000 --> 00:29:35,000
I might say, if I may, that when I first went to America, I was working at Johns Hopkins in a neuroimaging lab. And I found that in the first few weeks, people kept looking at me, but other puzzled when I say something and they go, really?

157
00:29:35,000 --> 00:29:52,000
And then I'd go, no, not really, don't mind. But I hadn't realized how much of whatever I said was to be read between the lines. It was amusing. It was putting a perspective on something. But they took everything deadly seriously.

158
00:29:52,000 --> 00:30:06,000
And this may be an aspect of having a melting pot of cultures where you can't rely on the usual sort of things to do with the way people say thing. And so you have to deal only with the explicit. But it's now become what we have to deal with everywhere.

159
00:30:06,000 --> 00:30:08,000
Sorry, carry on, please.

160
00:30:08,000 --> 00:30:22,000
I had a very similar, very similar experience of doing a long writer's workshop in California. This was over a decade ago now. And I was the only English person there. And I loved everyone on the workshop.

161
00:30:22,000 --> 00:30:23,000
Yes.

162
00:30:23,000 --> 00:30:37,000
But I realized about two weeks into it. And I said to one of my friends that I think maybe some of the people in the group are angry with me. And my friend touched me on the knee and said, they don't, they don't realize you're being ironic.

163
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:51,000
And I fought back for everything I said. And for, oh, no, they must think I'm a, I'm a terrible, terrible person. But what, so I want to dig into a bit more of what what's driving this literalism them is.

164
00:30:51,000 --> 00:31:06,000
I know this isn't what it is, but is, is the left hemisphere becoming bigger and and dominating us biologically? Or is there some kind of feedback mechanism in our culture? Or why are we becoming more and more?

165
00:31:06,000 --> 00:31:07,000
Yes.

166
00:31:07,000 --> 00:31:08,000
More left hemisphere?

167
00:31:08,000 --> 00:31:20,000
Well, as you rightly say, it's not that the left hemisphere is getting bigger. And in fact, it's of interest that the right hemisphere is slightly bigger and heavier than the left hemisphere in humans.

168
00:31:20,000 --> 00:31:40,000
What is happening, I think, is that, let me just refer here to one of my favorite philosophers, A. N. Whitehead, who said that a civilization flourishes until it starts to analyze itself.

169
00:31:40,000 --> 00:31:55,000
And I think that what happens is that in the way we have mainly lived for thousands and thousands of years is in harmony with nature, in harmony with society, in harmony with the myths, the rituals, the beliefs of our culture.

170
00:31:55,000 --> 00:32:10,000
And that these had been ample ways of alerting us to many kinds of truth that was not just a kind of tit for tat in the court of law way of debating things, but certain realities could not be encompassed in that way.

171
00:32:10,000 --> 00:32:12,000
But they didn't need to be.

172
00:32:12,000 --> 00:32:31,000
Well, what's happened in a largely deracinated culture where people have been torn away from their communities, dragged into the cities, more and more into a world made by machines, reflecting the left hemisphere as kind of a world all around them.

173
00:32:31,000 --> 00:32:48,000
They look out of the window, they see mechanisms, they see hard surfaces on a rigid grid, and they are no longer in touch with what I'm honored and grateful to be in touch with here, which is being surrounded by nature.

174
00:32:48,000 --> 00:32:51,000
And these things teach you, they speak to you.

175
00:32:51,000 --> 00:33:00,000
And so I think what's happened is that in this world in which we rely very much on discourse, you have to choose what it is you say.

176
00:33:00,000 --> 00:33:13,000
The first thing is that the right hemisphere's story is much more complex than that of the left hemisphere, and therefore requires a lot of effort to articulate, as I know, because I've articulated it at very great lengths in those two books.

177
00:33:13,000 --> 00:33:27,000
And a lot of people write to me and say, I mean countless people write to me and say, thank goodness, you've explained something that kind of knew at some level, but I just had no way of working it out, expressing it or defending it.

178
00:33:27,000 --> 00:33:36,000
And so I think what happens is that you have to make decisions, and the worst thing that can happen to you nowadays is to be said to be inconsistent.

179
00:33:36,000 --> 00:33:43,000
In fact, there's a great deal of wisdom in sometimes being inconsistent, because it's usually more than one side to a question.

180
00:33:43,000 --> 00:33:47,000
In fact, if only we realized that there's always more than one side to a question.

181
00:33:47,000 --> 00:33:57,000
We wouldn't have all the ridiculous self-righteousness, foot stamping, hysterical fit on the internet when somebody says something that somebody else doesn't agree with.

182
00:33:57,000 --> 00:34:01,000
Well, get real, get educated, this is what life is like.

183
00:34:01,000 --> 00:34:13,000
And so there's a kind of idiocy and ignorance that is spread across mass culture, which encourages black and white thinking, the loss of all the nuances.

184
00:34:13,000 --> 00:34:19,000
And in the process, all the subtle stuff is drowned out by sound bites.

185
00:34:19,000 --> 00:34:29,000
And I could say something which, if taken in context, meant almost exactly the opposite of what it would seem to be saying if it was just a sound bite taken out of its contact.

186
00:34:29,000 --> 00:34:37,000
And so incredible injustice is done to many people by something being taken out of context and whizzed around the world.

187
00:34:37,000 --> 00:34:44,000
And then next thing, they find that people are sort of treating them as a non-person.

188
00:34:44,000 --> 00:34:56,000
So we're involved in this process of distancing from nature and coming more and more into, well, I guess they are machine environments.

189
00:34:56,000 --> 00:34:59,000
They've been machines, they are somewhat machine-like.

190
00:34:59,000 --> 00:35:02,000
We can go back to a movie like Metropolis for its language.

191
00:35:02,000 --> 00:35:03,000
Wonderful.

192
00:35:03,000 --> 00:35:05,000
The whole city is a big machine.

193
00:35:05,000 --> 00:35:06,000
Yes.

194
00:35:06,000 --> 00:35:08,000
And that's 100 years ago.

195
00:35:08,000 --> 00:35:09,000
Yes.

196
00:35:09,000 --> 00:35:13,000
Now, we've advanced on a lot from there.

197
00:35:13,000 --> 00:35:19,000
So can we talk a bit about myth directly, I guess?

198
00:35:19,000 --> 00:35:30,000
Firstly, could I ask you, what are your formative mythic influences, like myths maybe that you grew up with or that are important to you?

199
00:35:30,000 --> 00:35:32,000
That's a good one.

200
00:35:32,000 --> 00:35:49,000
Well, I certainly didn't have a religious upbringing, not at least until I went to secondary school, where I was fortunate to be introduced to something I thought was beautiful and resonant and deep.

201
00:35:49,000 --> 00:35:53,000
So what did I find?

202
00:35:53,000 --> 00:35:56,000
I think my father was very literalistic.

203
00:35:56,000 --> 00:35:57,000
Bless him.

204
00:35:57,000 --> 00:36:03,000
I mean, he was a good man, a very good man, but he didn't have much time for poetry or music or anything like that.

205
00:36:03,000 --> 00:36:05,000
He liked facts.

206
00:36:05,000 --> 00:36:09,000
And I'm in favour of facts too, a lot of them.

207
00:36:09,000 --> 00:36:16,000
And I've defended my point of view with them, but I think there's more to life than that.

208
00:36:16,000 --> 00:36:24,000
Robert Graves' The White Goddess, actually, was a book I read in my teens, and I thought it was really, really important.

209
00:36:24,000 --> 00:36:37,000
I also read Helen Waddell's The Wandering Scholars, which was about the flourishing of poetry, music and dance in the late Middle Ages in Europe and what this meant for the culture.

210
00:36:37,000 --> 00:36:42,000
And then I didn't really follow the path.

211
00:36:42,000 --> 00:36:50,000
To this day, I haven't read The Hobbit and I haven't read The Lord of the Rings, and it's not that I don't think, you know, I don't respect Tolkien, I do.

212
00:36:50,000 --> 00:36:59,000
It's just rather, as I say, I don't these days have so much time for reading, you know, mythological books.

213
00:36:59,000 --> 00:37:12,000
I remember when I used to go say with my grandparents, I was encouraged to, and in those days we did, as we were told, to go and lie down after lunch, which gave them a chance to have a little nap and a bit of a rest.

214
00:37:12,000 --> 00:37:20,000
And in my bedroom, beside my table, there was a book, The Myths of Greece.

215
00:37:20,000 --> 00:37:32,000
And so I familiarised myself with Greek myths early on, and they were very, they touched me deeply, along with these Celtic myths that I'd heard from Robert Graves.

216
00:37:33,000 --> 00:37:36,000
And so these things were very important to me.

217
00:37:36,000 --> 00:37:46,000
And then later, you know, as I say, well, not later, but in my teens, I began to become intrigued and exploring further the mythos of Christianity.

218
00:37:46,000 --> 00:37:50,000
I mean, a word I use without any implication of this being true or false.

219
00:37:50,000 --> 00:38:00,000
And indeed, I think that myths have a kind of truth which is greater than factual truth, which as I say was a perception of the ancient Greeks anyway.

220
00:38:00,000 --> 00:38:06,000
So these are the things that have really intrigued me.

221
00:38:06,000 --> 00:38:14,000
And I also read, I did read the C. S. Lewis Narnia books, partly because I'd read the last battle when I was at school.

222
00:38:14,000 --> 00:38:24,000
But then when I had children of my own, I read them the whole Narnia seven-part thing, and they were completely rapt fired.

223
00:38:24,000 --> 00:38:29,000
And so was I, you know, I was thinking, fuck you, this is good stuff.

224
00:38:29,000 --> 00:38:35,000
So those are the things that, you know, it more or less obviously have populated my imagination.

225
00:38:35,000 --> 00:38:45,000
I was surprised when you said that you didn't have these things until a little bit later in your life.

226
00:38:45,000 --> 00:38:56,000
Because now it seems, I think many people are searching for something that they find in myth, and maybe you did that searching as well.

227
00:38:56,000 --> 00:39:14,000
And I think one of the problems with our perception of myth, and especially maybe the Christian mythos, is the idea that's held now that if you went back 300 years, everyone fully believed in Christ or in God or in the elements of the mythos.

228
00:39:14,000 --> 00:39:26,000
When, in fact, I think it's always been a thing that people have searched for, and a few people have found, rather than the actual held belief of everyone.

229
00:39:26,000 --> 00:39:33,000
The holding of fixed belief with certainty is not part of faith. It wouldn't be faith if it was certain.

230
00:39:33,000 --> 00:39:37,000
Faith is a matter of fidelity, in fact, that's the root of the word.

231
00:39:37,000 --> 00:39:49,000
In other words, it's something that you give your loyalty to, because you think it's great and noble, and it will lead you to places of revelation, of illumination, and enlightenment.

232
00:39:49,000 --> 00:40:02,000
And I think there's always been this tendency to think that signing up to six impossible things before breakfast is what religion is about, but it is not at all.

233
00:40:02,000 --> 00:40:19,000
It's about enriching the way in which you see the entirety of the world, so that once you start to see the world with different eyes, it has meaning, it has direction and purpose, it has beauty and truth in it.

234
00:40:19,000 --> 00:40:28,000
And these are the things that really seem to me to be the essence of a fulfilling life. Not to have those things is to be set adrift.

235
00:40:29,000 --> 00:40:43,000
This is backed by scientific research, but it's also intuitively obvious that the things that give us a sense of meaning are not invented by us, but are contacted by us.

236
00:40:43,000 --> 00:40:58,000
We are able to perceive them, and these are things we perceive with the help of nature, with the help of an intact tradition of a society, and through religions, or at any rate through a spiritual inclination.

237
00:40:58,000 --> 00:41:04,000
And these things are all opposed to the machine. There's no place in them for the mechanical, the simply mechanical.

238
00:41:04,000 --> 00:41:25,000
The simply mechanical is far too crude, leaves almost everything that's of important out. And so while it's useful, undeniably, it's only as good as the use is to which it's put, and often we're not the wisest assessors of what's going to happen when we start using it in a certain way.

239
00:41:25,000 --> 00:41:39,000
And we're already finding that we've set in motion things that we cannot now easily stop. It's the story of the Sorcerer's Apprentice, you know, who knew how to utter the spell that would cause the machine to get going, but doesn't know how to stop it.

240
00:41:39,000 --> 00:41:53,000
And now there's a lot of people who are warning us about the way in which this is going to impinge on humanity and perhaps take, if I may put it this way, the humanity out of humanity.

241
00:41:53,000 --> 00:42:12,000
So I think these things are massively important. And to embrace that mythos of Christianity is not to force yourself to believe anything, but to listen, to open your heart and mind to what is expressed for me most powerfully through the arts that it has generated.

242
00:42:12,000 --> 00:42:33,000
And so through the quite extraordinarily beautiful music, particularly of the Renaissance, and the extraordinarily fine paintings and the very moving poetry, and these things make clear to us things that otherwise we would ignore.

243
00:42:33,000 --> 00:42:45,000
That's my idea in a nutshell that it's not surprising that we're highly stressed, depressed, anxious, don't know what we're doing, don't know where we're going, because we've chucked all the means towards meaning out.

244
00:42:45,000 --> 00:42:54,000
I just want to emphasize again, you know, lots of people say, oh yes, you need these things like you make them up. Actually, you're in a padded cell, you can't see anything.

245
00:42:54,000 --> 00:43:02,000
It's a horrible business and the sooner it's over, the better. But let's cheer ourselves up along the way by pretending that there's something out there.

246
00:43:02,000 --> 00:43:11,000
No mate, there is something out there and we're part of it, by the way. Nature is not out there. Nature is in here and I am in nature.

247
00:43:11,000 --> 00:43:21,000
And the divine realm is not something out there or up in the sky. It's something that's in here and I'm in it. And society is not something other than me.

248
00:43:21,000 --> 00:43:25,000
I am in society and society is in me. These are the ways to say.

249
00:43:25,000 --> 00:43:44,000
But when people try to turn to something like the Christian mythos, maybe it's fair to say that what they get first is that left-brained literal interpretation of the mythos, which is in its way dogmatic.

250
00:43:44,000 --> 00:43:52,000
And they're meeting that with their own left hemisphere interpretation, which is where the arguments come up from.

251
00:43:52,000 --> 00:44:01,000
So I don't want to give this to you because this starts to become a bit like a guru question, I guess.

252
00:44:01,000 --> 00:44:09,000
But how do we then reconnect with our right hemisphere? That's a too big a question, I think.

253
00:44:09,000 --> 00:44:26,000
But maybe just in that mythic sense, when someone is asking that question, well, the Minotaur doesn't literally exist or we don't have any historical evidence for X or Y.

254
00:44:26,000 --> 00:44:29,000
What is an answer to that, do you think?

255
00:44:29,000 --> 00:44:41,000
Well, not everything that is very real is tenable down. It's not capable of being fixed.

256
00:44:41,000 --> 00:44:50,000
The left hemisphere wants things that are fixed and it can fix them in language and it can fix them by tracing a course in history.

257
00:44:50,000 --> 00:44:57,000
But while that is a very useful idea, don't get me wrong, I don't disparage that, I use that all the time.

258
00:44:57,000 --> 00:45:04,000
My mind is quite wrathful, actually. But it also realizes, using reason, that reason is not everything.

259
00:45:04,000 --> 00:45:11,000
And Pascal himself said, reason is feeble indeed if it cannot explain that reason is not everything.

260
00:45:11,000 --> 00:45:25,000
And of course, for people who like scientific and mathematical proofs, Gödel's theorem actually proves that there are things that are certainly true within a certain framework but cannot be proved within that frame.

261
00:45:25,000 --> 00:45:35,000
So I think one needs to free oneself from the idea that one builds up a picture of reality from little nuggets that one puts together.

262
00:45:35,000 --> 00:45:39,000
Well, I've got a fact there and a fact there, I put them here. Of course, they don't seem to mean anything.

263
00:45:39,000 --> 00:45:47,000
Well, no, first of all, you've taken them out of context. They only mean something in the context that there is.

264
00:45:47,000 --> 00:45:54,000
And so we need that business of bringing together, but it doesn't start from the bits.

265
00:45:54,000 --> 00:46:00,000
It starts from the fact that things are already here and that our mind wants to break them up.

266
00:46:00,000 --> 00:46:08,000
So one has to think in broader patterns over greater distances in time and in space.

267
00:46:08,000 --> 00:46:20,000
So we are connected with others across time and space. We are as connected with our ancestors as we are with our descendants.

268
00:46:20,000 --> 00:46:25,000
And we have loyalties to both and duties to both.

269
00:46:25,000 --> 00:46:34,000
And we're also connected to people all around the world as we more and more perceive through the damage that has been done by industrialization.

270
00:46:34,000 --> 00:46:41,000
And so I think the first thing is to perceive the world differently.

271
00:46:41,000 --> 00:46:46,000
Often in a religion, people will say, and they're right.

272
00:46:46,000 --> 00:46:52,000
To me, say a Christian, it's not to believe the following things and never doubt them.

273
00:46:52,000 --> 00:46:58,000
But it is to see with new eyes, to feel with a new heart.

274
00:46:58,000 --> 00:47:03,000
There is a medieval prayer, which I think is very important, God be in my head.

275
00:47:03,000 --> 00:47:09,000
And it's very short. It's only a few lines. You know, God be in my head and in my understanding.

276
00:47:09,000 --> 00:47:13,000
God be in my eyes and in my looking. God be in my mouth and in my speaking.

277
00:47:13,000 --> 00:47:18,000
God be in my heart and in my thinking. God be at my end and at my departing.

278
00:47:18,000 --> 00:47:27,000
And that very neat and short poem is very much about what I was talking about, internalizing something that is bigger than you.

279
00:47:27,000 --> 00:47:30,000
And so the first thing is to change the cast of mind.

280
00:47:30,000 --> 00:47:34,000
And people might say, well, how do I do that without working from step to step?

281
00:47:34,000 --> 00:47:39,000
But that, again, is the left hemisphere. This is actually not the way things work.

282
00:47:39,000 --> 00:47:50,000
Many things come as a moment of insight, as an aha moment, a re-jigging of a shape of a form, so that you see it anew.

283
00:47:50,000 --> 00:48:01,000
And, boringly, as a psychiatrist, a lot of work that I have done is helping people to see for themselves what it is they need to do.

284
00:48:01,000 --> 00:48:08,000
And that, you know, if you make the mistake, as when I was wet behind the ears and haven't had a lot of experience in psychology,

285
00:48:08,000 --> 00:48:13,000
I used to do it just to tell people what they needed to do. It wasn't that I was wrong. I was right.

286
00:48:13,000 --> 00:48:17,000
But the thing is, it's no good telling people until they see it for themselves.

287
00:48:17,000 --> 00:48:22,000
And what's more, what they will see is greater than anything. I can tell them and more appropriate to them.

288
00:48:22,000 --> 00:48:30,000
So that's what I'd say. I mean, of course, I can become banal and say there are things to do, like practice mindfulness, which I think is very important.

289
00:48:31,000 --> 00:48:42,000
Practice being compassionate and grateful. These are simple things and listen more to music and attend to it.

290
00:48:42,000 --> 00:48:46,000
Don't just, you know, have it on in the background and not pay attention to it.

291
00:48:46,000 --> 00:48:54,000
So, and to read myths and re-engage really with a mythology.

292
00:48:54,000 --> 00:48:58,000
And the best mythologies are religious mythologies, in my view.

293
00:48:58,000 --> 00:49:03,000
I mean, they're the accumulation of wisdom with so many people over so long.

294
00:49:03,000 --> 00:49:11,000
The idea that little me can in my lifetime with a little bit that I know improve on that is hubris, isn't it?

295
00:49:11,000 --> 00:49:15,000
Isn't that just an extraordinary act of arrogance?

296
00:49:15,000 --> 00:49:22,000
So it's not to say that, you know, traditions aren't changing. They're changing all the time. They flow.

297
00:49:22,000 --> 00:49:29,000
But the only way in which we can make things go in the direction that we think is better is by engaging with that tradition.

298
00:49:29,000 --> 00:49:35,000
It's like a plug that you want to go somewhere. You don't cut it off from its stem and roots and stick it on the wall.

299
00:49:35,000 --> 00:49:38,000
You train it there, and that's what a tradition is like.

300
00:49:38,000 --> 00:49:45,000
That's very cool. I think maybe I can push on that a bit.

301
00:49:45,000 --> 00:49:54,000
So I think for people today, there is a great difficulty engaging with these religious traditions,

302
00:49:54,000 --> 00:50:03,000
which I would say are kind of the great mythos, mythoses of our civilization.

303
00:50:03,000 --> 00:50:05,000
Yeah, mythos.

304
00:50:05,000 --> 00:50:12,000
So I think we're engaging instead with what you might call a synthetic mythos.

305
00:50:12,000 --> 00:50:20,000
And two of the great figures in that happening. One is Joseph Campbell and his hero's journey or his mono myth.

306
00:50:20,000 --> 00:50:29,000
So I would say it's kind of like a synthesizing. He takes all of this pattern from great mythic traditions,

307
00:50:29,000 --> 00:50:39,000
especially the Christian tradition, and presents it as a pattern which is then picked up by storytellers,

308
00:50:39,000 --> 00:50:43,000
famously Star Wars, but hundreds of other movies.

309
00:50:43,000 --> 00:50:50,000
And these movies seem to be consistently very powerful for people. They have a real effect.

310
00:50:50,000 --> 00:50:59,000
And then Campbell's ideas are really coming from Carl Jung and his ideas about archetypes and so on.

311
00:50:59,000 --> 00:51:07,000
So could you comment perhaps a bit on the idea of could a synthetic mythos have value in that way,

312
00:51:07,000 --> 00:51:17,000
and also about perhaps a relationship between Jung and your own thinking on the hemispheres and meaning of myth?

313
00:51:17,000 --> 00:51:27,000
Yes, there is a very strong link between my thinking and Jung, and it really wasn't from reading Jung that I generated what I think.

314
00:51:27,000 --> 00:51:33,000
It worked the other way that I worked from the neuroscience to see what the picture was.

315
00:51:33,000 --> 00:51:40,000
And it wasn't always the one that people would anticipate. And yet I found constantly resonances with Jung's work.

316
00:51:40,000 --> 00:51:47,000
And with Hillman, you know, James Hillman, who was a disciple, if you like, of Jung.

317
00:51:47,000 --> 00:51:58,000
