01:33:22,000 --> 01:33:25,000
and they think myth is just made up.

718
01:33:25,000 --> 01:33:28,000
So now I've just put the idea on the table for them that,

719
01:33:28,000 --> 01:33:34,000
no, actually, myth is a bit more like reality than August.

720
01:33:34,000 --> 01:33:37,000
The myth is at least necessary.

721
01:33:37,000 --> 01:33:44,000
And I think they would, at this point, actually have some anger about it.

722
01:33:44,000 --> 01:33:53,000
Because they have this perception of myth as lie,

723
01:33:53,000 --> 01:34:00,000
and they don't want a lie asserted as real.

724
01:34:00,000 --> 01:34:05,000
So I just channeled them to that length there.

725
01:34:05,000 --> 01:34:08,000
So what more could we say to them?

726
01:34:08,000 --> 01:34:14,000
Well, the first thing is to be aware when you're finding something makes you angry.

727
01:34:14,000 --> 01:34:19,000
I don't mean just in the way that a psychiatrist would say,

728
01:34:19,000 --> 01:34:23,000
that's probably showing you a conflict in you that you're not recognizing.

729
01:34:23,000 --> 01:34:30,000
But I mean that anger is absolutely the main mode of operation of the left hemisphere.

730
01:34:30,000 --> 01:34:33,000
It's always angry, and it's always right, by the way.

731
01:34:33,000 --> 01:34:37,000
It always knows what the truth is, thinks it does.

732
01:34:37,000 --> 01:34:39,000
But of course, you know, from my work,

733
01:34:39,000 --> 01:34:43,000
that actually it's often frankly deluded, completely deluded,

734
01:34:43,000 --> 01:34:47,000
but it's emphatic that what it thinks it knows is the only story.

735
01:34:47,000 --> 01:34:52,000
Thinking you know the only story is also, I would say, a bit of an alarm bell.

736
01:34:52,000 --> 01:34:55,000
Are you really sure about that?

737
01:34:55,000 --> 01:35:00,000
And what about listening to a few other people and seeing if that has rings of bells?

738
01:35:00,000 --> 01:35:09,000
The other thing I'd say is that, what about poetry?

739
01:35:09,000 --> 01:35:14,000
Poetry takes us to places that are not just literal scientific facts,

740
01:35:14,000 --> 01:35:18,000
but I'm prepared to say that poetry is lies.

741
01:35:18,000 --> 01:35:23,000
If so, I can't really help you, I'm just interested to know.

742
01:35:23,000 --> 01:35:30,000
Because if you think that, you're going to miss out on an enormous amount of experience

743
01:35:30,000 --> 01:35:35,000
that is profoundly, it speaks to us as embodying truths,

744
01:35:35,000 --> 01:35:44,000
truths that are much harder to express in the language one might use for a dishwasher instruction manual.

745
01:35:44,000 --> 01:35:47,000
And so what are we really saying?

746
01:35:47,000 --> 01:35:57,000
It was only with Locke in the 18th century that people started to talk about myths and poetry and so on as lies.

747
01:35:57,000 --> 01:36:02,000
And one has to be very careful about that,

748
01:36:02,000 --> 01:36:09,000
because there are things that can be believed as unshakably true

749
01:36:09,000 --> 01:36:15,000
because we've proved them according to what we know, which we now know are not true.

750
01:36:15,000 --> 01:36:21,000
So until Rutherford, we thought that the universe really obeyed Newtonian mechanics,

751
01:36:21,000 --> 01:36:27,000
but there's ample evidence over the last 100 years that this is simply not the case.

752
01:36:27,000 --> 01:36:31,000
And we're now seeing, as I say in biology, that there's evidence,

753
01:36:31,000 --> 01:36:36,000
that there are whatever you like to call them, form fields or whatever,

754
01:36:36,000 --> 01:36:41,000
that guide the development of an organism that are nowhere to be found in the genome.

755
01:36:41,000 --> 01:36:44,000
We believed it was all in the genome, then we sequenced the genome,

756
01:36:44,000 --> 01:36:50,000
and we found there wasn't, not only was there wasn't enough information, but there was hardly any.

757
01:36:50,000 --> 01:36:53,000
And it was so small the amount of information.

758
01:36:53,000 --> 01:37:00,000
It was many orders of magnitude, too little, to express what it is that organisms can do.

759
01:37:00,000 --> 01:37:05,000
So we're now opening our minds again and thinking, well, maybe there's something else going on here.

760
01:37:05,000 --> 01:37:09,000
Think about that. You come to different conclusions.

761
01:37:09,000 --> 01:37:15,000
And I think it's worth mentioning that almost all the physicists of the 20th century,

762
01:37:15,000 --> 01:37:21,000
the great ones who one thinks of was having developed quantum mechanics,

763
01:37:21,000 --> 01:37:28,000
people like Niels Bohr, Max Planck, Heisenberg, Schwerdinger, and so on.

764
01:37:28,000 --> 01:37:34,000
I don't need to go through the panoply, but practically all of them had a great deal of time

765
01:37:34,000 --> 01:37:37,000
for religious myths.

766
01:37:37,000 --> 01:37:42,000
And in fact, there is, I quote in the book,

767
01:37:42,000 --> 01:37:46,000
evidence about the beliefs of Nobel Prize winners.

768
01:37:46,000 --> 01:37:49,000
The Nobel Prize has been awarded since 1900.

769
01:37:49,000 --> 01:37:55,000
So we have evidence over the last 120 years of the religious beliefs of people who won Nobel prizes.

770
01:37:55,000 --> 01:38:01,000
Are scientists less religious than the people who are at the top of their game in the humanities?

771
01:38:01,000 --> 01:38:09,000
No. In the humanities, the rate of people who at some point in their life have been disbelievers in the divine

772
01:38:09,000 --> 01:38:14,000
is about 35%. It's still not a majority, but it's pretty large.

773
01:38:14,000 --> 01:38:19,000
And as you go down into the sciences, it's something like,

774
01:38:19,000 --> 01:38:25,000
it's something like 89% for biology, about 7% for chemistry,

775
01:38:25,000 --> 01:38:30,000
and it's 4.9, 4.7% for physicists.

776
01:38:30,000 --> 01:38:35,000
They are the most religious people. And it's also the hardest science, frankly.

777
01:38:35,000 --> 01:38:44,000
So I just ask all these people who just know they're right and get very angry when someone says something they don't agree with,

778
01:38:44,000 --> 01:38:49,000
to, you know, calm down, take a deep breath,

779
01:38:49,000 --> 01:38:56,000
consider that you might not know everything, that the things you believe are right might only temporarily seem to be right,

780
01:38:56,000 --> 01:39:02,000
and are just a stepping stone on reaching greater truth, greater wisdom.

781
01:39:02,000 --> 01:39:08,000
That's all I can say. The great thing as a psychiatrist is that you know there are people who can't help.

782
01:39:08,000 --> 01:39:14,000
And say, you stop banging your head against, you know, I'm never going to win this person over.

783
01:39:14,000 --> 01:39:20,000
So you stop worrying about it. There are always going to be people who don't see what it is you're talking about.

784
01:39:21,000 --> 01:39:26,000
Everybody has to sit with the truth as they know, and the consequences of that.

785
01:39:26,000 --> 01:39:32,000
So good luck, you know, if you're one of the angry young men or angry old men.

786
01:39:32,000 --> 01:39:34,000
There we go.

787
01:39:34,000 --> 01:39:42,000
Well, I think it's something we've lost in our teaching, because we're not allowed to offend students.

788
01:39:42,000 --> 01:39:49,000
It's that you can't really teach anything without pushing people to the point of anger,

789
01:39:49,000 --> 01:39:52,000
because it's part of our development.

790
01:39:52,000 --> 01:39:59,000
Can I put one more big question on the table for you before we wrap up, which is the future.

791
01:39:59,000 --> 01:40:07,000
So obviously the future is a big part of science fiction, and I think that's because the future has become very important to us.

792
01:40:07,000 --> 01:40:13,000
We don't have another world to think about, so we think about the future of this world.

793
01:40:14,000 --> 01:40:21,000
And you mentioned actually Stalin and Mao, I think, just now.

794
01:40:21,000 --> 01:40:28,000
So that was one kind of utopian vision of the future, maybe a future with no injustice,

795
01:40:28,000 --> 01:40:33,000
assuming we give them the credit that they actually believed what they were saying.

796
01:40:33,000 --> 01:40:40,000
So we have that utopian future, but the most powerful future seems to be progress.

797
01:40:40,000 --> 01:40:48,000
The future will have progressed, primarily technologically will have better technology.

798
01:40:48,000 --> 01:40:53,000
But none of these seem to be particularly compelling futures for us at the moment.

799
01:40:53,000 --> 01:41:02,000
We think more actually about Armageddon and dystopia and the destruction of the world, maybe via climate change.

800
01:41:02,000 --> 01:41:17,000
So I wonder if you have thoughts on the future and maybe a big question about maybe what might a more hemispherically balanced future look like?

801
01:41:17,000 --> 01:41:21,000
What might a more right hemisphere future look like, perhaps?

802
01:41:23,000 --> 01:41:30,000
Well, of course, the talking of myths, the myth of progress is a very singular idea.

803
01:41:30,000 --> 01:41:35,000
I mean, it was never espoused before by any other culture, but it's become ours since Enlightenment,

804
01:41:35,000 --> 01:41:40,000
which was a very valuable but also a futuristic movement that believed that it knew everything

805
01:41:40,000 --> 01:41:46,000
and understood everything and that the future would be ever more wonderful.

806
01:41:46,000 --> 01:41:53,000
I read a wonderful German haiku the other day, which basically translated goes,

807
01:41:53,000 --> 01:41:57,000
in the past it was good, then everything became much better.

808
01:41:57,000 --> 01:41:59,000
If only it were good again.

809
01:41:59,000 --> 01:42:10,000
Anyway, I think predicting the future is famously a mug's game, so I don't know.

810
01:42:10,000 --> 01:42:15,000
But I think it's very wise of us to think about the consequences of our actions.

811
01:42:15,000 --> 01:42:26,000
And I take that the cautionary principle has a great deal in it and that there are certain steps you can take that will be extremely hard to reverse.

812
01:42:26,000 --> 01:42:34,000
And we've talked a bit about that already, how a cage that's made out of self-referring loops will be very difficult to break out of.

813
01:42:34,000 --> 01:42:38,000
So I do worry about that, and I think it's the way we're going.

814
01:42:38,000 --> 01:42:51,000
And it's certainly the case that the greatest crimes in the history of humanity in terms of their scope and severity have been conducted by people who thought they knew how to make a better world.

815
01:42:51,000 --> 01:42:57,000
So we have Lenin and Stalin and Mao and Paul Parton and so on.

816
01:42:58,000 --> 01:43:10,000
People who are a little bit more humble and want to work with people to make them to change their understanding of other people, to be more tolerant of other people, not less tolerant of them, would be important.

817
01:43:10,000 --> 01:43:18,000
So I think what I would say is there's a more hemisphere balance future, would be a beautiful place to live.

818
01:43:18,000 --> 01:43:31,000
It would be one where, yes, science made progress, but it wasn't trampled by, as we now know, that science is being trampled by a form of political correctness and wokeness.

819
01:43:31,000 --> 01:43:37,000
There are certain things that are true, but are known to be true, but can't be said and are dismissed.

820
01:43:37,000 --> 01:43:45,000
And other things that, because they promote the received narrative, are not good science, but are not as published.

821
01:43:45,000 --> 01:44:03,000
And a recent piece of research shows that scientists, the majority, nearly all, in fact, in the words of the piece of research, scientists consulted in the US, said that they, to some extent, self-centered what it was they said or thought or investigated.

822
01:44:03,000 --> 01:44:08,000
So it would be a world that was more in touch with truth, but also a kinder one.

823
01:44:08,000 --> 01:44:21,000
Because, you know, for all that we're trying to achieve this wonderfully balanced and lovely world, I've noticed during my lifetime a great loss of joy and peacefulness.

824
01:44:21,000 --> 01:44:38,000
You know, in the world I grew up, we know more sort of, you know, the things that trouble us now as huge problems, maybe we should have done, but in fact, there was more understanding between the sexes.

825
01:44:38,000 --> 01:44:45,000
There was probably less anxiety between and fear between the races.

826
01:44:45,000 --> 01:44:52,000
And I know that's a difficult area to go into, because there are all kinds of points of view, and I respect that it's complicated.

827
01:44:52,000 --> 01:44:57,000
But I think it's also worth considering that we haven't necessarily made it all better.

828
01:44:57,000 --> 01:45:07,000
In fact, what we've done, whatever we have done, is produce a world which is wracked with mental illness, and in which people feel adrift and don't know what to say or what to believe.

829
01:45:07,000 --> 01:45:18,000
So I think in that world we would have returned to a sense of purpose, which was anchored around the great values of goodness, beauty and truth, and a sense of the sacred.

830
01:45:18,000 --> 01:45:32,000
And we would begin to work together rather than work against one another, not feeding conflict and adversity, and I'm right, you're wrong, and I need power, and you must have less.

831
01:45:32,000 --> 01:45:38,000
But instead, a sort of seeing that we can work together.

832
01:45:38,000 --> 01:45:47,000
This is so elementary that it's been part of all the people who have really helped humanity forward in the last, you know, in the 20th century.

833
01:45:48,000 --> 01:46:03,000
And indeed of Martin Luther King, and Nelson Mandela, I mean, we need to work together to cooperate, because if we don't, we'll die.

834
01:46:03,000 --> 01:46:05,000
I mean, there's no question about it.

835
01:46:05,000 --> 01:46:11,000
And you know, interestingly, the story of evolution is not one of constant opposition and aggression.

836
01:46:11,000 --> 01:46:12,000
That comes into it.

837
01:46:12,000 --> 01:46:14,000
It's a very important part of the picture.

838
01:46:14,000 --> 01:46:20,000
But actually, the species that have been most successful have been those who learned to cooperate.

839
01:46:20,000 --> 01:46:25,000
So cooperation is a big part of becoming whatever we are.

840
01:46:25,000 --> 01:46:37,000
And I would say that if we could adopt a little more humility about what we know, faced with an insight into actually how little we understand.

841
01:46:37,000 --> 01:46:49,000
If we could rediscover compassion and the art of gently listening to people in a non-patronizing way, but being able to discuss whatever.

842
01:46:49,000 --> 01:46:51,000
Nothing should be off limits.

843
01:46:51,000 --> 01:46:56,000
We should be able to talk about it in a reasonable way, and hear one another out.

844
01:46:56,000 --> 01:47:03,000
And a sense of wonder at the beautiest nature of the world, which is not just a foregone mechanism.

845
01:47:03,000 --> 01:47:10,000
These things would ultimately alter the way in which we experience life.

846
01:47:10,000 --> 01:47:17,000
And I think that we need to be gravitating towards them as fast as we can.

847
01:47:17,000 --> 01:47:24,000
Recovering civility, teaching children in school, how to negotiate, how to argue two sides of a question,

848
01:47:24,000 --> 01:47:29,000
how to arbitrate between warring parties,

849
01:47:29,000 --> 01:47:34,000
how to do something that is normally only taught to people too late in life when their marriage is on the rocks,

850
01:47:34,000 --> 01:47:40,000
which is how to talk to another person and hear what it is they're saying.

851
01:47:40,000 --> 01:47:44,000
So, you know, in couple counseling there's a thing you do where you say,

852
01:47:44,000 --> 01:47:46,000
no, you say what it is.

853
01:47:46,000 --> 01:47:48,000
No, no, you'll have your moment in a minute.

854
01:47:48,000 --> 01:47:51,000
Let him speak or let her speak.

855
01:47:51,000 --> 01:47:54,000
And when that's finished, then the other person's allowed to reply.

856
01:47:54,000 --> 01:47:59,000
What they must do is to say back what it is they've heard the other person say.

857
01:47:59,000 --> 01:48:03,000
And very often that is so revealing as you find that there was a misconception.

858
01:48:03,000 --> 01:48:05,000
That wasn't what they were saying at all.

859
01:48:05,000 --> 01:48:07,000
And so there is common ground.

860
01:48:07,000 --> 01:48:13,000
And finding that common ground is what we need.

861
01:48:13,000 --> 01:48:17,000
So, I don't know the answer to these things.

862
01:48:17,000 --> 01:48:19,000
I can give pointers.

863
01:48:19,000 --> 01:48:21,000
I can give hope.

864
01:48:21,000 --> 01:48:25,000
I can say we only are asked not to solve massive problems on our own,

865
01:48:25,000 --> 01:48:28,000
to cooperate with others towards ends we believe in,

866
01:48:28,000 --> 01:48:32,000
and to bring integrity into our own lives.

867
01:48:32,000 --> 01:48:37,000
And as much as possible, avoid saying things we know to be wrong.

868
01:48:37,000 --> 01:48:45,000
Avoid furthering things that will restrict freedom and restrict the expression of beauty.

869
01:48:45,000 --> 01:48:50,000
And re-sophisticate our idea of what good is, which comes from the heart.

870
01:48:50,000 --> 01:48:52,000
It's not following rules.

871
01:48:52,000 --> 01:48:54,000
It's not ticking boxes.

872
01:48:54,000 --> 01:49:03,000
It's about something that's in here, a disposition of the soul.

873
01:49:03,000 --> 01:49:08,000
Well, much of that sounds like ancient wisdom.

874
01:49:08,000 --> 01:49:11,000
And I think maybe one of the...

875
01:49:11,000 --> 01:49:17,000
I hope, well, I've observed this already in telling people about your work,

876
01:49:17,000 --> 01:49:21,000
and in talking with people who are already familiar with it,

877
01:49:21,000 --> 01:49:29,000
is that this placing this understanding of the dual hemispheres

878
01:49:29,000 --> 01:49:36,000
gives us in itself a myth, a story to understand this through.

879
01:49:36,000 --> 01:49:43,000
So, I could say to people, listen to the good.

880
01:49:43,000 --> 01:49:46,000
But that doesn't make sense to people.

881
01:49:46,000 --> 01:49:52,000
But I think to say, maybe we can work from our right hemisphere for a while,

882
01:49:52,000 --> 01:49:54,000
with all of the attached meanings to that,

883
01:49:54,000 --> 01:50:01,000
is actually, it is in itself a way into all of the things which you're saying,

884
01:50:01,000 --> 01:50:03,000
which we can all agree with,

885
01:50:03,000 --> 01:50:07,000
but we don't have a central signal to discuss it through.

886
01:50:07,000 --> 01:50:11,000
And I hope that your work is actually giving that to people.

887
01:50:11,000 --> 01:50:14,000
Are you seeing that in...

888
01:50:14,000 --> 01:50:18,000
Are you seeing some impact of your ideas in the world when you talk to people?

889
01:50:18,000 --> 01:50:21,000
It's hard to judge, because, of course, to some extent,

890
01:50:21,000 --> 01:50:27,000
the people that I encounter are going to be the people who are more open to it.

891
01:50:27,000 --> 01:50:37,000
But I certainly do get a colossal amount of feedback that is so heartening to me,

892
01:50:37,000 --> 01:50:42,000
because I never foresaw that by writing, I thought about an interesting topic

893
01:50:42,000 --> 01:50:44,000
that some people would fix on and say,

894
01:50:44,000 --> 01:50:47,000
yeah, interesting, maybe we should investigate this more.

895
01:50:47,000 --> 01:50:49,000
I thought basically it would all be forgotten,

896
01:50:49,000 --> 01:50:53,000
but it hasn't been and that people see the meaning that I'm trying to propagate

897
01:50:53,000 --> 01:50:55,000
is extraordinary heartening.

898
01:50:55,000 --> 01:50:59,000
Young people in particular are more open to this.

899
01:50:59,000 --> 01:51:07,000
The people who are a problem are the established smug intellectuals.

900
01:51:07,000 --> 01:51:12,000
They're practically all white and they think they know what's best

901
01:51:12,000 --> 01:51:18,000
for people of all races and people of different sexes and so on.

902
01:51:18,000 --> 01:51:23,000
So they think they know, and the story is a played out story.

903
01:51:23,000 --> 01:51:28,000
And what we're experiencing is a conflict between an enforced ideology

904
01:51:28,000 --> 01:51:31,000
which sees people in system and what our heart is telling us.

905
01:51:31,000 --> 01:51:33,000
And that's a very uncomfortable place to be.

906
01:51:33,000 --> 01:51:36,000
And I think that's what's causing a lot of the grief,

907
01:51:36,000 --> 01:51:41,000
the fear, the panic, the anxiety, the stress and the gloom.

908
01:51:41,000 --> 01:51:47,000
If we could find a world in which people spoke recognizable truths to us again,

909
01:51:47,000 --> 01:51:49,000
this would be wonderful.

910
01:51:49,000 --> 01:51:53,000
Because one's heart sings when one hears something that one can respond to

911
01:51:53,000 --> 01:51:56,000
and that one knows in one's heart is right.

912
01:51:56,000 --> 01:51:58,000
I mean, you say people don't know where to go for truth,

913
01:51:58,000 --> 01:52:04,000
but I think they kind of do because they can see the big picture with their right hemisphere

914
01:52:04,000 --> 01:52:08,000
and they can see the way in which this is being discussed and unpacked

915
01:52:08,000 --> 01:52:15,000
and they can see in it something different from what it is they're being served up all the time

916
01:52:15,000 --> 01:52:17,000
and worrying about.

917
01:52:17,000 --> 01:52:21,000
I am in that sense a hopeful pessimist, as I often say.

918
01:52:21,000 --> 01:52:24,000
I'm hopeful in the sense that I always have great hope in humanity.

919
01:52:24,000 --> 01:52:27,000
You don't know what they'll come up with. They're amazingly resourceful.

920
01:52:27,000 --> 01:52:29,000
They're wonderful beings, actually.

921
01:52:29,000 --> 01:52:34,000
One of the things I'm very opposed to is the constant derogation of humanity.

922
01:52:34,000 --> 01:52:36,000
Yes, of course, we've made an almighty cock up.

923
01:52:36,000 --> 01:52:38,000
That's absolutely true.

924
01:52:38,000 --> 01:52:42,000
And there's lots of things we've done that we would now not do in that way.

925
01:52:42,000 --> 01:52:45,000
But there is something amazing about human beings.

926
01:52:45,000 --> 01:52:48,000
If we can live in harmony with the rest of the natural world,

